Each lightning bolt heats the air

270
0:12:10.26,000 --> 0:12:12,000
to 44,000 degrees Fahrenheit --

271
0:12:12.26,000 --> 0:12:15,000
hotter than the surface of the Sun.

272
0:12:15.26,000 --> 0:12:17,000
What if we could use

273
0:12:17.26,000 --> 0:12:19,000
these electromagnetic pulses

274
0:12:19.26,000 --> 0:12:21,000
as beacons,

275
0:12:21.26,000 --> 0:12:24,000
beacons in a moving network

276
0:12:24.26,000 --> 0:12:27,000
of powerful transmitters?

277
0:12:27.26,000 --> 0:12:29,000
Experiments suggest

278
0:12:29.26,000 --> 0:12:34,000
that lightning could be the next GPS.

279
0:12:34.26,000 --> 0:12:37,000
Electrical pulses form the thoughts in our brains.

280
0:12:37.26,000 --> 0:12:4,000
Using a grid the size of your thumb,

281
0:12:40.26,000 --> 0:12:42,000
with 32 electrodes

282
0:12:42.26,000 --> 0:12:44,000
on the surface of his brain,

283
0:12:44.26,000 --> 0:12:46,000
Tim uses his thoughts

284
0:12:46.26,000 --> 0:12:52,000
to control an advanced prosthetic arm.

285
0:12:52.26,000 --> 0:12:54,000
And his thoughts

286
0:12:54.26,000 --> 0:12:56,000
made him reach for Katie.

287
0:12:56.26,000 --> 0:13:,000
This is the first time

288
0:13:00.26,000 --> 0:13:02,000
a human has controlled a robot

289
0:13:02.26,000 --> 0:13:05,000
with thought alone.

290
0:13:05.26,000 --> 0:13:07,000
And it is the first time

291
0:13:07.26,000 --> 0:13:09,000
that Tim has held Katie's hand

292
0:13:09.26,000 --> 0:13:11,000
in seven years.

293
0:13:11.26,000 --> 0:13:13,000
That moment mattered

294
0:13:13.26,000 --> 0:13:15,000
to Tim and Katie,

295
0:13:15.26,000 --> 0:13:17,000
and this green goo

296
0:13:17.26,000 --> 0:13:2,000
may someday matter to you.

297
0:13:20.26,000 --> 0:13:22,000
This green goo

298
0:13:22.26,000 --> 0:13:25,000
is perhaps the vaccine that could save your life.

299
0:13:25.26,000 --> 0:13:28,000
It was made in tobacco plants.

300
0:13:28.26,000 --> 0:13:3,000
Tobacco plants

301
0:13:30.26,000 --> 0:13:33,000
can make millions of doses of vaccine

302
0:13:33.26,000 --> 0:13:36,000
in weeks instead of months,

303
0:13:36.26,000 --> 0:13:38,000
and it might just be

304
0:13:38.26,000 --> 0:13:42,000
the first healthy use of tobacco ever.

305
0:13:42.26,000 --> 0:13:44,000
And if it seems far-fetched

306
0:13:44.26,000 --> 0:13:47,000
that tobacco plants could make people healthy,

307
0:13:47.26,000 --> 0:13:5,000
what about gamers that could solve problems

308
0:13:50.26,000 --> 0:13:52,000
that experts can't solve?

309
0:13:52.26,000 --> 0:13:54,000
Last September,

310
0:13:54.26,000 --> 0:13:56,000
the gamers of Foldit

311
0:13:56.26,000 --> 0:13:58,000
solved the three-dimensional structure

312
0:13:58.26,000 --> 0:14:,000
of the retroviral protease

313
0:14:00.26,000 --> 0:14:03,000
that contributes to AIDS in rhesus monkeys.

314
0:14:03.26,000 --> 0:14:05,000
Now understanding this structure

315
0:14:05.26,000 --> 0:14:09,000
is very important for developing treatments.

316
0:14:09.26,000 --> 0:14:11,000
For 15 years,

317
0:14:11.26,000 --> 0:14:13,000
it was unsolved

318
0:14:13.26,000 --> 0:14:15,000
in the scientific community.

319
0:14:15.26,000 --> 0:14:17,000
The gamers of Foldit

320
0:14:17.26,000 --> 0:14:2,000
solved it in 15 days.

321
0:14:20.26,000 --> 0:14:22,000
Now they were able to do so

322
0:14:22.26,000 --> 0:14:24,000
by working together.

323
0:14:24.26,000 --> 0:14:26,000
They were able to work together

324
0:14:26.26,000 --> 0:14:28,000
because they're connected by the Internet.

325
0:14:28.26,000 --> 0:14:31,000
And others, also connected to the Internet,

326
0:14:31.26,000 --> 0:14:35,000
used it as an instrument of democracy.

327
0:14:35.26,000 --> 0:14:37,000
And together

328
0:14:37.26,000 --> 0:14:4,000
they changed the fate of their nation.

329
0:14:40.26,000 --> 0:14:43,000
The Internet is home to two billion people,

330
0:14:43.26,000 --> 0:14:46,000
or 30 percent of the world's population.

331
0:14:46.26,000 --> 0:14:49,000
It allows us to contribute

332
0:14:49.26,000 --> 0:14:51,000
and to be heard

333
0:14:51.26,000 --> 0:14:53,000
as individuals.

334
0:14:53.26,000 --> 0:14:56,000
It allows us to amplify

335
0:14:56.26,000 --> 0:14:59,000
our voices and our power

336
0:14:59.26,000 --> 0:15:01,000
as a group.

337
0:15:01.26,000 --> 0:15:04,000
But it too had humble beginnings.

338
0:15:04.26,000 --> 0:15:07,000
In 1969, the internet was but a dream,

339
0:15:07.26,000 --> 0:15:09,000
a few sketches on a piece of paper.

340
0:15:09.26,000 --> 0:15:12,000
And then on October 29th,

341
0:15:12.26,000 --> 0:15:14,000
the first packet-switched message was sent

342
0:15:14.26,000 --> 0:15:17,000
from UCLA to SRI.

343
0:15:17.26,000 --> 0:15:2,000
The first two letters of the word "Login,"

344
0:15:20.26,000 --> 0:15:22,000
that's all that made it through --

345
0:15:22.26,000 --> 0:15:24,000
an L and an O --

346
0:15:24.26,000 --> 0:15:26,000
and then a buffer overflow crashed the system.

347
0:15:26.26,000 --> 0:15:29,000
(Laughter)

348
0:15:29.26,000 --> 0:15:31,000
Two letters,

349
0:15:31.26,000 --> 0:15:34,000
an L and an O,

350
0:15:34.26,000 --> 0:15:38,000
now a worldwide force.

351
0:15:38.26,000 --> 0:15:41,000
So who are these scientists and engineers

352
0:15:41.26,000 --> 0:15:44,000
at a magical place called DARPA?

353
0:15:44.26,000 --> 0:15:47,000
They are nerds,

354
0:15:47.26,000 --> 0:15:5,000
and they are heroes among us.

355
0:15:50.26,000 --> 0:15:52,000
They challenge existing perspectives

356
0:15:52.26,000 --> 0:15:54,000
at the edges of science

357
0:15:54.26,000 --> 0:15:58,000
and under the most demanding of conditions.

358
0:15:58.26,000 --> 0:16:,000
They remind us

359
0:16:00.26,000 --> 0:16:02,000
that we can change the world

360
0:16:02.26,000 --> 0:16:04,000
if we defy the impossible

361
0:16:04.26,000 --> 0:16:08,000
and we refuse to fear failure.

362
0:16:08.26,000 --> 0:16:1,000
They remind us

363
0:16:10.26,000 --> 0:16:13,000
that we all have nerd power.

364
0:16:13.26,000 --> 0:16:17,000
Sometimes we just forget.

365
0:16:17.26,000 --> 0:16:19,000
You see, there was a time

366
0:16:19.26,000 --> 0:16:21,000
when you weren't afraid of failure,

367
0:16:21.26,000 --> 0:16:24,000
when you were a great artist or a great dancer

368
0:16:24.26,000 --> 0:16:26,000
and you could sing, you were good at math,

369
0:16:26.26,000 --> 0:16:29,000
you could build things, you were an astronaut,

370
0:16:29.26,000 --> 0:16:31,000
an adventurer, Jacques Cousteau,

371
0:16:31.26,000 --> 0:16:33,000
you could jump higher, run faster,

372
0:16:33.26,000 --> 0:16:36,000
kick harder than anyone.

373
0:16:36.26,000 --> 0:16:38,000
You believed in impossible things

374
0:16:38.26,000 --> 0:16:4,000
and you were fearless.

375
0:16:40.26,000 --> 0:16:44,000
You were totally and completely in touch

376
0:16:44.26,000 --> 0:16:48,000
with your inner superhero.

377
0:16:48.26,000 --> 0:16:51,000
Scientists and engineers

378
0:16:51.26,000 --> 0:16:54,000
can indeed change the world.

379
0:16:54.26,000 --> 0:16:56,000
So can you.

380
0:16:56.26,000 --> 0:16:58,000
You were born to.

381
0:16:58.26,000 --> 0:17:,000
So go ahead,

382
0:17:00.26,000 --> 0:17:02,000
ask yourself,

383
0:17:02.26,000 --> 0:17:05,000
what would you attempt to do

384
0:17:05.26,000 --> 0:17:07,000
if you knew you could not fail?

385
0:17:07.26,000 --> 0:17:09,000
Now I want to say,

386
0:17:09.26,000 --> 0:17:12,000
this is not easy.

387
0:17:12.26,000 --> 0:17:14,000
It's hard to hold onto this feeling,

388
0:17:14.26,000 --> 0:17:16,000
really hard.

389
0:17:16.26,000 --> 0:17:18,000
I guess in some way,

390
0:17:18.26,000 --> 0:17:2,000
I sort of believe it's supposed to be hard.

391
0:17:20.26,000 --> 0:17:23,000
Doubt and fear always creep in.

392
0:17:23.26,000 --> 0:17:26,000
We think someone else, someone smarter than us,

393
0:17:26.26,000 --> 0:17:28,000
someone more capable,

394
0:17:28.26,000 --> 0:17:31,000
someone with more resources will solve that problem.

395
0:17:31.26,000 --> 0:17:33,000
But there isn't anyone else;

396
0:17:33.26,000 --> 0:17:36,000
there's just you.

397
0:17:36.26,000 --> 0:17:38,000
And if we're lucky,

398
0:17:38.26,000 --> 0:17:4,000
in that moment,

399
0:17:40.26,000 --> 0:17:43,000
someone steps into that doubt and fear,

400
0:17:43.26,000 --> 0:17:46,000
takes a hand and says,

401
0:17:46.26,000 --> 0:17:49,000
"Let me help you believe."

402
0:17:49.26,000 --> 0:17:52,000
Jason Harley did that for me.

403
0:17:52.26,000 --> 0:17:55,000
Jason started at DARPA

404
0:17:55.26,000 --> 0:17:57,000
on March 18th, 2010.

405
0:17:57.26,000 --> 0:18:01,000
He was with our transportation team.

406
0:18:01.26,000 --> 0:18:03,000
I saw Jason nearly every day,

407
0:18:03.26,000 --> 0:18:05,000
sometimes twice a day.

408
0:18:05.26,000 --> 0:18:07,000
And more so than most,

409
0:18:07.26,000 --> 0:18:1,000
he saw the highs and the lows,

410
0:18:10.26,000 --> 0:18:14,000
the celebrations and the disappointments.

411
0:18:14.26,000 --> 0:18:18,000
And on one particularly dark day for me,

412
0:18:18.26,000 --> 0:18:2,000
Jason sat down

413
0:18:20.26,000 --> 0:18:23,000
and he wrote an email.

414
0:18:23.26,000 --> 0:18:25,000
He was encouraging,

415
0:18:25.26,000 --> 0:18:27,000
but firm.

416
0:18:27.26,000 --> 0:18:29,000
And when he hit send,

417
0:18:29.26,000 --> 0:18:32,000
he probably didn't realize what a difference it would make.

418
0:18:32.26,000 --> 0:18:34,000
It mattered to me.

419
0:18:34.26,000 --> 0:18:36,000
In that moment

420
0:18:36.26,000 --> 0:18:39,000
and still today

421
0:18:39.26,000 --> 0:18:41,000
when I doubt,

422
0:18:41.26,000 --> 0:18:44,000
when I feel afraid,

423
0:18:44.26,000 --> 0:18:46,000
when I need to reconnect

424
0:18:46.26,000 --> 0:18:48,000
with that feeling,

425
0:18:48.26,000 --> 0:18:51,000
I remember his words,

426
0:18:51.26,000 --> 0:18:53,000
they were so powerful.

427
0:18:53.26,000 --> 0:18:56,000
Text: "There is only time enough to iron your cape

428
0:18:56.26,000 --> 0:18:59,000
and back to the skies for you."

429
0:19:00.26,000 --> 0:19:02,000
